   File: Components/Pages/Admin/UserManagement.razor

   PURPOSE: Admin-only page for creating users, assigning roles,
   and deleting users. Only users with the "Admin" role can access it.

   KEY CONCEPTS:
   • @attribute [Authorize(Roles = "Admin")]  →  Role-based access control.
     Non-admin users get an "access denied" response, not the page content.
   • @rendermode InteractiveServer  →  Enables interactive features
     (button clicks, form bindings) via a real-time SignalR connection.
     Without this, the page is static HTML with no interactivity.
   • @inject  →  Requests a service from dependency injection (DI).
     Similar to constructor injection in regular C# classes.
   • @bind  →  Two-way data binding between an HTML input and a C# variable.
     When the user types in the input, the variable updates automatically.
   • @onclick  →  Binds a button click to a C# method.

   ⚠️ IMPORTANT: DbContext SCOPING IN BLAZOR SERVER
   In Blazor Server (@rendermode InteractiveServer), scoped services like
   UserManager and its underlying DbContext live for the ENTIRE lifetime
   of the SignalR circuit (i.e., as long as the browser tab is open).
   This causes two problems:
     1. DbContext is NOT thread-safe. If the admin clicks two buttons
        quickly, two async operations hit the same DbContext simultaneously,
        causing InvalidOperationException.
     2. The long-lived DbContext accumulates tracked entities and never
        refreshes, serving stale data if another admin modifies users.

   SOLUTION: Instead of injecting UserManager directly, we inject
   IServiceProvider and create a fresh DI scope inside each method.
   Each scope gets its own short-lived UserManager + DbContext that
   is disposed when the method completes. This is the Microsoft-
   recommended pattern for database access in interactive Blazor components.
   ━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━ *@

